This analysis uses the Our World in Data global CO‚ÇÇ dataset covering emissions by country from 1750 to 2021. The dataset includes 79 features covering emissions by fuel source, GDP, population, temperature change, and land-use change.

Preprocessing: Filtered to 1950+, removed aggregate regions (e.g. ‚ÄòAfrica‚Äô, ‚ÄòWorld‚Äô), engineered fuel-mix shares, GDP per capita, emission levels, and log-transforms.

üéØ 8. Key Findings & Conclusions

CO‚ÇÇ Regression

Ridge Regression achieved R¬≤ = 1.0000. Source-specific CO‚ÇÇ columns (coal, oil, gas) are the strongest predictors, as total CO‚ÇÇ is largely their sum. Population and GDP provide additional signal.

Emission Classification

MLP Neural Network achieved F1 = 0.9838. Tree-based models excel at distinguishing emission levels. Total CO‚ÇÇ, per-capita metrics, and fuel-mix shares are the key discriminators.

Growth-Rate Forecasting

GR ‚Äì Gradient Boosting achieved R¬≤ = 0.2007. Year-over-year CO‚ÇÇ change is inherently noisy and harder to predict; lagged CO‚ÇÇ levels and economic indicators provide moderate predictive power.

Country Clustering

K-Means identified 4 distinct country clusters. Countries group primarily by total emission volume and per-capita intensity, revealing a clear divide between industrialised high-emitters and developing nations.
